{{for|"tweener" tennis rackets|Tweener racket}}
[[File:Granwilly-vilas-1978.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Guillermo Vilas]] performing the ''Gran Willy'' shot.]]
The '''tweener''' or '''between-the-legs shot''' is a difficult [[tennis shot]] where a player hits the ball between his or her legs. It is typically performed facing away from the opponent, when the player attempts to recover a [[lob (tennis)|lob]] and has no time to turn back around, and hits the ball backward between their legs. Forward-facing tweeners, sometimes called "front tweeners", are also occasionally employed. In competitive matches the tweener is a crowd-pleasing, seldom used last resort, but it is a common trick shot in exhibitions. Players who famously executed the backward shot include the pioneer [[Guillermo Vilas]] (whose version was called the "Gran Willy"), [[Yannick Noah]], [[Ilie Nastase]], [[Gabriela Sabatini]] (whose version became known as "the Sabatweenie"), [[Roger Federer]], [[Juan Martín del Potro]], [[Nick Kyrgios]], [[Daria Kasatkina]], [[Agnieszka Radwańska]] and [[Simona Halep]].<ref name=Grasso>{{cite book |last= Grasso|first= John |year= 2011 |title= Historical Dictionary of Tennis |url= https://books.google.com/?id=W39oSS7c2xAC&pg=PA288&dq=Tweener+tennis+shot#v=onepage&q=Tweener%20tennis%20shot&f=false |publisher= Scarecrow Press |page= 288 |isbn= 0810872374 |access-date= July 6, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=Siegel>{{cite news |last= Siegel |first= Alan |date= September 8, 2010|title= Roger Federer and the History of Tennis Trick Shots |url= https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2010/09/roger-federer-and-the-history-of-tennis-trick-shots/62549/ |newspaper= [[The Atlantic]] |access-date= July 6, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Clarey>{{cite news |last= Clarey |first= Christopher|date= August 31, 2010|title= Federer Hits His Greatest Shot Ever, A Second Time|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/01/sports/tennis/01federer.html?_r=0 |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |access-date= July 6, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Dent>{{cite web |url= http://theclassical.org/articles/everybodys-doing-the-tweener|title= Everybody's Doing the Tweener |last1= Dent |first1= Mark |date= May 10, 2012|website= theclassical.org |publisher= |access-date= July 6, 2015|quote=}}</ref>

==History==
The origin of the backward shot is unclear; both Argentine Guillermo Vilas and French player Yannick Noah claim to have invented it. Both players used it somewhat regularly in the 1970s.<ref name=Siegel/><ref name=Clarey/> Vilas was inspired by an advertisement where a [[polo]] player hit a backwards shot between his horse's hind legs.<ref>{{cite web|title = La vidriera |author = |work= [[La Nación]] |date= 20 September 2006 |url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/archivo/Nota.asp?nota_id=841879 |accessdate = 20 January 2008}}</ref> He debuted his version in a 1974 exhibition match at the courts of Obras Sanitarias Club in Buenos Aires. Then he employed it in an official match in Indianapolis the following year against the spaniard player [[Manuel Orantes]]; the shot became known as the "Gran Willy" ("the great willy") after him.<ref>{{cite web|title = Vilas volvió a hacer la "Gran Willy" a cien metros de la primera vez|trans-title = Vilas has returned to make the "Gran Willy" a hundred meters from the first time|work = Diario Buenos Aires|date = 8 December 2006|url = http://www.diariobuenosaires.com.ar/nota2.asp?IDNoticia=17666|accessdate = 20 January 2008|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071008183031/http://www.diariobuenosaires.com.ar/nota2.asp?IDNoticia=17666|archivedate = 8 October 2007|df = dmy-all}}</ref> Romanian Ilie Năstase, who pioneered a backward over-the-shoulder shot known as the "[[Bucharest Backfire]]", also executed the backward tweener during the 1970s.<ref name=Siegel/><ref name=Clarey/>

In the 1980s, players employing the backward tweener shot included the German player [[Boris Becker]], the Swede [[Stefan Edberg]], and Argentine [[Gabriela Sabatini]], whose version became known as "the Sabatweenie". American [[Andre Agassi]] used it in the 1990s.<ref name=Siegel/> In the 21st century, Swiss player Roger Federer hit tweeners on several notable occasions, further popularizing the shot. He successfully hit a backward tweener for a [[Glossary of tennis#W|winner]] to give himself [[Glossary of tennis#M|match point]] in the [[2009 US Open – Men's Singles|2009 US Open]] semifinal, which he called "the greatest shot I ever hit in my life."<ref name=Grasso/><ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/tennis/article-1213286/US-OPEN-2009-VIDEO--This-greatest-shot-admits-Roger-Federer-beating-Novak-Djokovic.html Roger Federer: "It's the greatest shot I ever hit in my life]. Mail Online. 14 September 2009.</ref> Federer has also used front-facing tweeners on several occasions.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Federer hits through-the-legs winner at Qatar Open|author =|publisher = ESPN|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=tennis&id=5987714|accessdate = 6 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= White |first= Jim |date= July 2, 2015 |title= Wimbledon 2015: Roger Federer delights centre court in Sam Querrey demolition |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/tennis/wimbledon/11714260/Wimbledon-2015-Roger-Federer-delights-centre-court-in-Sam-Querrey-demolition.html |newspaper= The Telegraph |access-date= July 6, 2015}}</ref> A high jump front-facing tweener was also notably executed by [[Mary Pierce]] during the quarter finals of the 2000 French Open.

